((SELECT id FROM "legacy".crops WHERE label = 'Barley, Winter' and zone = 7),(SELECT id FROM "legacy".data_keys WHERE key = 'cover_crop_description'),'Upright small grain. Widely used in the Northeast. Best small grain for drought, heat, salty, or alkaline soils. Not suitable for wet or acid soils. Winter barley typically needs vernalization (overwintering) to produce stalk/head/seed. May stay short and fail to flower if planted in spring. Quick growth and high biomass if fertility is good. Good weed suppressor, N scavenger, forage producer. Retains feed quality after heading. Good nurse crop for legumes. Use care when including as a cover crop in a small grain rotation (host for same diseases and pests). Bloom timing and height match crimson clover, rapeseed when used in a mix. Planted earlier in fall, matures earlier in spring than wheat. More winter-hardy than oat, less than wheat and rye. Better fall growth and tillers more than wheat and rye but more prone to frost damage.'),
